liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The House of Representatives economics committee is grilling ANZ chief executive Shayne Elliott on branch closures. Mr Elliott says ANZ had 678 branches in 2017 and now has 391 branches. Most of the 287 closures have been in major cities. Mr Elliott says ANZ has 250 branches in major cities, 75 branches in inner regional areas, 47 branches in outer regional and 19 branches in remote or very remote areas. He says 96 per cent of transactions are done online, with only 8 per cent of customers using branches because they don't do any digital banking at all. "Most of them are actually, they're more likely to be small business operators," Mr Elliott told the committee." "Small businesses have more complex needs than individuals." "So retail customers generally pretty well service on a on a digital basis."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 287 ANZ branches closed since 2017

children.content: The House of Representatives economics committee is grilling ANZ chief executive Shayne Elliott on branch closures.
Mr Elliott says ANZ had 678 branches in 2017 and now has 391 branches.
Most of the 287 closures have been in major cities.
Mr Elliott says ANZ has 250 branches in major cities, 75 branches in inner regional areas, 47 branches in outer regional and 19 branches in remote or very remote areas.
He says 96 per cent of transactions are done online, with only 8 per cent of customers using branches because they don't do any digital banking at all.
"Most of them are actually, they're more likely to be small business operators," Mr Elliott told the committee."
"Small businesses have more complex needs than individuals."
"So retail customers generally pretty well service on a on a digital basis."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: ANZ chief executive Shayne Elliott is giving evidence to the House of Representatives economics committee. He says loan arrears remain low despite interest rates rising steeply to 4.1 per cent over the past year. "Only $6 of every $1,000 in our Australian home loan portfolio was overdue by more than 90 days. "That is better than it was before the pandemic." Mr Elliott says ANZ customers are "faring extremely well" and people are still saving, although the bank has seen a modest increase in customers "reaching out to us for help". "Credit standards are higher than those leading into prior times of stress. "And this means that fewer people are getting into trouble."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australia and the European Union have failed to reach an agreement on a free trade deal. Negotiations have been underway since 2018 into ways Australian producers can export agricultural products into the European market, which the EU has pushed back against. The EU has also threatened the right of Australian producers to use names such as "prosecco" and "feta" due to its strict "geographic indicators". Trade Minister Don Farrell travelled to Brussels this week in an attempt to break the deadlock, but he says Australia could not accept the deal that was offered. "My job is to get the best result for Australia." "We weren't able to achieve that on this occasion." The National Farmers Federation says it supports the Australian government's decision to continue working on the deal. NFF chief executive Tony Mahar say he applauds Senator Farrell and the negotiating team for "rejecting a sub-standard deal". "We're hopeful that with some grit and goodwill from both sides we can get this thing done in a way that benefits everyone, including Aussie farmers," Mr Mahar says. "Australia should not have to accept a deal which is inferior to that of other countries." Here's more from political reporter Chantelle Al-Khouri.
